preferred-citation:
  type: thesis
  title: >
    Integrated Security Assessment Framework for Smart Contracts: A
    Defense-in-Depth Approach to Cyberdefense
  authors:
    - family-names: Boiero
      given-names: Fernando
  institution:
    name: "Universidad de la Defensa Nacional (UNDEF) - IUA Córdoba"
  thesis-type: "Master's Thesis"
  department: "Cyberdefense"
  year: 2025
  abstract: >
    Historical thesis snapshot by Fernando Boiero, distinct from the current
    three-author paper metadata above. This thesis presents MIESC, a
    comprehensive security assessment framework for smart contracts based on
    defense-in-depth principles. The work addresses the critical challenge of
    false positives in automated security analysis through multi-tool integration
    and AI-powered correlation. Key contributions include:
    (1) Novel MCP-based multi-agent architecture for collaborative cyberdefense,
    (2) Empirical validation on curated and real-world corpora, with ensemble
    recall approximately double the best single-tool baseline (43.2% recall,
    Durieux et al. 2020), (3) Automated compliance mapping to international
    standards, (4) Open-source implementation enabling reproducible
    security research. On SmartBugs-curated (143 contracts), the static and
    intelligence profile reports 95.8% recall, and on 11 real-world DeFi exploits
    MIESC detects 9 of 11 cases (81.8% recall, 95% Wilson confidence interval
    [52%, 95%]). Every quantitative claim is traced to a released per-claim matrix
    and its source artifacts for independent reproduction.
